<REASONING>
In the first round, there is no prior information about the tendencies or strategies of the other players. The optimal initial contribution should balance between fostering cooperation and safeguarding personal gain.

Contributing all 20 coins maximizes the potential group payoff, as it will be multiplied by 1.48 and redistributed. However, if others contribute minimally, my payoff will suffer when the group payoff is divided back to all players.

To cultivate a positive and cooperative dynamic while maintaining an element of caution, I will begin by contributing a moderate portion of my coins, encouraging others to contribute without risking too much of my personal endowment. This contribution sets a cooperative precedent, potentially encouraging others to do the same in subsequent rounds.

A contribution of 10 coins is a balanced choice, signaling willingness to cooperate without overcommitting the entire private fund.
</REASONING>
<CONTRIBUTE>
10
</CONTRIBUTE>

<REASONING>
The goal in a public goods game is to maximize my individual payoff while also considering the potential communal benefits of contributing. If all players contribute all of their coins, the total payoff would be maximized. However, others might choose to free-ride by contributing less and benefiting from others' contributions.

If I contribute 20 coins, the total pooled contribution will be larger, leading to a greater multiplier effect, but it may not be optimal if others do not contribute similarly. If I contribute nothing, I maximize my private fund but risk punishment or lose out on communal gains.

To balance these risks, an initial moderate contribution is a strategic move. It signals willingness to cooperate, encourages others to contribute, and reduces punitive actions against me. Based on typical behavior in such games, starting with a moderate contribution helps in gauging others' strategies in subsequent rounds.

Thus, I decide to contribute a middle-ground amount.
</REASONING>
<CONTRIBUTE>
10
</CONTRIBUTE>
